entially zeroing out coefficients. L2 adds squared penalty, encouraging small nonzero weights and smoother solutions, which helps prevent overfitting, especially when dealing with multicollinearity.\\\"\\n\\nSTEP 5: SCORING\\n---------------\\nScale: 1 (Poor) – 5 (Excellent)\\n\\nQ1 (Model Deployment)\\n Criteria: infrastructure best practices, monitoring, automation, scalability\\n Score: 5/5\\n\\nQ2 (Missing Data)\\n Criteria: statistical rigor, pattern analysis, validation, justification of methods\\n Score: 4/5\\n\\nQ3 (Challenging Project)\\n Criteria: problem identification, solution design, impact, communication of results\\n Score: 5/5\\n\\nQ4 (Continuous Learning)\\n Criteria: diversity of sources, proactiveness, application of knowledge\\n Score: 5/5\\n\\nQ5 (Regularization)\\n Criteria: technical accuracy, clarity, applicability, understanding of trade-offs\\n Score: 5/5\\n\\nOverall Score = (5 + 4 + 5 + 5 + 5) / 5 = 4.8\\n\\nSTEP 6: FINAL EVALUATION REPORT\\n--------------------------------\\nCandidate: Jane Smith\\nPosition: Data Scientist\\nEvaluation Date: 2024-06-16\\n\\nSummary:\\nJane exhibits excellent skills in model deployment, data handling, and continuous learning. Her responses were precise, structured, and demonstrated best practices. With 3+ years of relevant experience and strong technical credentials, she fully meets the job requirements and exceeds expectations in several areas.\\n\\nRecommendation:\\nStrongly recommend extending an offer for the Data Scientist position. Her strong theoretical knowledge combined with practical experience makes her an ideal candidate for our team.\\n\\n------------------------------------------------------------\\nEnd of Full Evaluation Process\\n------------------------------------------------------------\\n```\\n\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-28T12:33:33.322646\"\n}"}
